Implements steno "count-bank" encoding: turning an `@count` key spec into bit-weighted keys, and the arithmetic to merge/inject those keys into a stroke's mid/right sub-banks. This is the mechanism behind numeric suffix strokes (e.g. encoding a repeat count as a combination of vowel/right-bank keys).

Core convention, easy to get wrong when editing: `count_bank` treats the spec string as LSB-first — the first char listed gets weight 1, second gets weight 2, etc. (`AOEU` → weights 1,2,4,8). Each spec key must be either a mid-bank (vowel) key or a right-bank key per `is_mid`/`is_right` from `keys.rs`; anything else is a `StrokeError`. `max` is `2^width - 1` computed from the last bit's weight, with overflow saturating to `u32::MAX` rather than panicking — and weight computation itself uses `checked_mul` and errors out ("too long to encode") if a spec would need more than 32 bits.

Four public entry points:
- `count_bank(spec: &str) -> Result<CountBank, StrokeError>` — parses the spec into `CountBank { bits: Vec<CountBit>, max: u32 }`.
- `merge_strokes(a: &str, b: &str) -> Result<String, StrokeError>` — parses both sub-strokes via `parse_stroke`, unions left/mid/right key sets, ORs the `num` flag, and re-renders. Errors if any key appears in both strokes (checked bank-by-bank via private `merge_bank`), not just overall — so a left-bank collision is caught even if mid/right are clean.
- `add_key(segment: &str, key: char) -> Result<String, StrokeError>` — inserts one vowel/right-bank key into a parsed segment; errors if the key is already present or isn't a valid mid/right key (left-bank keys are rejected here even though `merge_strokes` handles left banks).
- `apply_count(segment: &str, spec: &str, count: u32) -> Result<String, StrokeError>` — builds the bank from `spec`, validates `count <= bank.max`, then walks the bits and inserts each bit's key into the segment's mid or right bank when that bit is set in `count`; errors if a count key is already present in the segment (partial mutation of `keys` may have already occurred before the error is returned, since insertion happens bit-by-bit rather than pre-checked).

Depends on `super::keys` for `KeySet`, `is_mid`, `is_right`, `parse_stroke`, and `render_stroke` — this file has no independent notion of stroke layout; any change to bank boundaries (what counts as mid vs. right) must happen in `keys.rs` and will silently change which keys `count_bank`/`add_key` accept.